---
import SiteLayout from '../layouts/SiteLayout.astro';
---

<SiteLayout
	title="Ideas"
	description="Guiding ideas behind OrgOps: legible operations, explicit interfaces, composable skills, and human-in-the-loop automation."
>
	<header class="hero">
		<h1>Ideas</h1>
		<p class="lede">
			A few guiding ideas behind OrgOps. This is intentionally lightweight: enough to understand the shape of the
			system without reading the whole codebase.
		</p>
	</header>

	<section class="section">
		<h2>Make operations legible</h2>
		<p>
			If an agent can do it, you should be able to see it: inputs, outputs, and the chain of decisions.
		</p>
		<p>
			In practice: every tool call and side effect shows up as an event (and often a process log), so you can answer
			“what ran?” without guessing.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="section">
		<h2>Prefer explicit interfaces</h2>
		<p>
			Typed events and command envelopes beat ad-hoc strings. They’re easier to validate, test, and evolve.
		</p>
		<p>
			Example: prefer
			<code>{`{"type":"channel.command.requested","payload":{...}}`}</code>
			over “run deploy now”.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="section">
		<h2>Small core, composable edges</h2>
		<p>
			Keep the runtime minimal. Add integrations and automation as skills so teams can move fast without turning the
			system into a black box.
		</p>
		<p>
			A skill is just code + schemas + conventions — versioned alongside your repo.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="section">
		<h2>Human-in-the-loop by default</h2>
		<p>
			Agents should collaborate with humans. OrgOps is designed for coordination, not silent autonomy.
		</p>
		<p>
			If something matters (money, prod, customer impact), route it through an explicit approval step.
		</p>
	</section>
</SiteLayout>

<style>
	.hero {
		padding: 1.5rem 0 1rem;
	}
	.lede {
		max-width: 70ch;
		color: rgb(var(--muted));
	}
	.section {
		margin-top: 2.25rem;
		max-width: 75ch;
	}
	code {
		white-space: normal;
		overflow-wrap: anywhere;
		word-break: break-word;
		max-width: 100%;
	}
</style>
